WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:01.294
n gram methods.

00:03.137 --> 00:08.528
So there are a number of tricks right here that are, I think, not understood until this day.

00:09.190 --> 00:13.278
For example, the question is, how do you sample these negative samples?

00:14.020 --> 00:15.222
Right here,

00:16.822 --> 00:24.332
This basically says get k words from your vocabulary at random according to this distribution right here.

00:24.813 --> 00:25.914
Now, how are you going to do that?

00:26.495 --> 00:29.139
Basically, you have a spectrum of options.

00:29.599 --> 00:34.386
The one side of the spectrum is going to be completely uniform.

00:35.147 --> 00:38.391
Okay, we sample each word with the same probability.

00:38.371 --> 00:45.663
And the other side of the spectrum is something like sample this according to their unigram.

00:46.545 --> 00:47.586
These are two different things.

00:48.568 --> 00:50.692
They're opposites in this fashion.

00:51.132 --> 00:58.184
So here you say, hey, some words appear way, way, way more often than other words.

00:58.685 --> 01:01.490
Shouldn't we prefer them when we sample, right?

01:01.570 --> 01:04.615
Shouldn't we, if we have a corpus,

01:04.595 --> 01:08.260
And shouldn't we sample from the corpus?

01:09.101 --> 01:16.090
And if in the corpus, one word appears 50 times more than the other word, then shouldn't we sample that 50 times more as a negative?

01:16.250 --> 01:20.996
Because it's, you know, so abundant and it should give a higher classification accuracy.

01:21.396 --> 01:26.162
Whereas on the other hand, you could say, no, no, no, we should simply sample every word in our dictionary uniformly.

01:27.063 --> 01:32.290
They came up with something in between, which they say,

01:32.270 --> 01:38.238
Both NC and negative sampling have noise distribution as a free parameter.

01:38.338 --> 01:47.091
We investigated a number of choices and found that the unigram distribution raised to the three-quarter power, i.e.

01:47.231 --> 01:58.767
unigram to the three-quarter, outperformed significantly the unigram and uniform distributions for both NC and NEGA on every task we tried, including language modeling.

01:58.747 --> 02:22.535
This I think is a mystery until today and it actually turned out that this exponent right here is Magically much better than like the exponent of one or even the exponent of one half like you might be reasonably assumed that the square root You know might be something but the three-quarters I think turned out to be very good and very mystical.

02:22.555 --> 02:23.556
So what does it all?

02:23.536 --> 02:24.377
What does it mean?

02:24.437 --> 02:29.742
It means that you have kind of a balance between words that appear often and words that don't appear often.

02:30.182 --> 02:40.972
Usually in these kind of things, you have a power law where you have very few words that appear very often, and then you have, okay, that's the tail shouldn't go up, but you have a very long tail of words.

02:42.053 --> 02:53.003
And what you want to do is, in this case, you want to sample these words here more, but they appear so much more often than if you simply sample according to their unigram distribution,

02:52.983 --> 02:56.169
You'll basically not regard these words right here.

02:56.270 --> 03:01.440
You'll forget about them and your performance will suffer because they do appear every now and then.

03:02.061 --> 03:15.247
So what you want to do is you want to push those down a little bit and the optimal amount for the little bit turns out to be to raise it to the three-quartered.

03:17.552 --> 03:20.037
Strange, but you know turned out to work well.

